Part I - Prosper Dataset Exploration¶

by Ntombi Mashila¶

Introduction¶

The Prosper data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 81 variables and 113,937 records capturing information on loans disbursed by Prosper Bank. Some of the features relate to the characteristics of the borrower at the time the account was opened.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in finding out if the risk rating (ProsperScore) is being assigned correctly to borrowers and in understanding the relationship between the risk score and the other variables in the dataset. I will focus on the loans that have resulted in a net loss for the bank. I will be using the feature LP_NetPrincipalLoss to filter out this population.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Features that relate to how the borrower manages existing credit such as the DebtToIncomeRatio, BankcardUtilization, CurrentDelinquencies, TotalTrades, TradesNeverDelinquent,TradesOpenedLast6Months, OpenRevolvingAccounts and TotalProsperLoans. Other interesting features relating to the borrower could be IncomeRange, ProsperScore, Occupation and EmploymentStatusDuration. Features of interest relating to the loan could be LoanMonthsSinceOrigination, LoanOriginalAmount and Term.

#Lets map the ListingCategory codes to the code decribtion and create a count plot
Category_map={
    0 : "Not Available",
    1 : "Debt Consolidation",
    2 : "Home Improvement", 
    3 : "Business",
    4 : "Personal Loan", 
    5 : "Student Use",
    6 : "Auto",
    7 : "Other", 
    8 : "Baby&Adoption", 
    9 : "Boat",
    10 : "Cosmetic Procedure",
    11 : "Engagement Ring", 
    12 : "Green Loans", 
    13 : "Household Expenses", 
    14 : "Large Purchases",
    15 : "Medical/Dental", 
    16 : "Motorcycle",
    17 : "RV", 
    18 : "Taxes",
    19 : "Vacation",
    20 : "Wedding Loans"}
def map_code_to_cat(loan):
    if loan['ListingCategory (numeric)'] in Category_map.keys():
        label=Category_map[loan['ListingCategory (numeric)']]
        return label
    else:
        return loan['ListingCategory (numeric)']
Loss_df['ListingCategory (numeric)']=Loss_df.apply(map_code_to_cat, axis=1)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The Prosper score appears to follow a normal distribution due to it's bell shape. The variable did not require any transformation.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distribution of LoanMonthsSinceOrigination seemed unusual, as if two distibutions were plotted on the same axis. The bimodal distribution can be explained by the fact that the loans have terms up to 60 months, after the repayment period has lapsed, defaulted loans will continue to be in arrears for months or years until they are eventually charged off

The distribution of StatedMonthlyIncome was positioned at the lower end of it's axis, which indicated the presence of outliers. Most of the distribution was at 70,000 or lower, so I trimmed the variable up to 100,000. This excluded two values, one above 100,000 and the second above 200,000.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

My main variable of interest Prosper score was not correlated with any of the other variables. But LP_NetPrincipalLoss has some intersting relationships.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

LP_NetPrincipalLoss was strongly correlated with Original Loan amount. There was also an interaction between Term and LP_NetPrincipalLoss. The longer the term of the loan the higher the loss amount. This could be a factor of longer term loans having larger repayment amounts. I also saw that certain categories of loans like wedding loans and business loans can be risky for the lender to issue out as the losses can get very large.

In [401]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8,8])
sb.pointplot(data = Loss_df, x = 'ProsperScore', y = 'LP_NetPrincipalLoss', hue = 'IsBorrowerHomeowner',
           palette = 'Blues', linestyles = '', dodge = 0.2);

The NetPrincipalLoss increases as the Risk grade increases for both home owners and non home owners. In other words there are customers who were asssigned a good risk rating at origination but ended up defaulting and costing the bank money, and the better the score at origination, the more money lost on these defaults. Across the risk scale, home owners have larger losses than the non-home owners.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The pointplot of ProsperScore against NetprincipalLoss revealed a relationship between the two variables that was not evident from looking at the correlation matrix and scatter plot. We see that the principal loss amount increases as the Risk rating increases and that home owners have larger loss amounts than non-home owners.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Yes, for loans with a term of 36 months, the loss amounts are higher for home owners than non home owners while for other loan terms the losses are the same between the 2 groups.

Conclusions¶

Prosper score is not strongly correlated to any of the other variables in the dataset.

With certain visualisations, the relationship between the ProsperScore and other variables is hidden due to the size of the data. But when the variables are summarised like in a point plot some relationships do emerge, like how the loss increases as the score increases. This might help Prosper to focus on revising their lending strategy for higher scoring customers to mitigate the loss for this group. And since the loss amount is correlated with Original Loan amount, they could reduce the amount of credit available for certain groups of borrowers.
